<h4 id="text-alignment">Text Alignment</h4>

<p>This project will have you using left-justified type. If you look at the graphic below, youâ€™ll see that this is different than left-aligned text. With left-justified text, you have no rag. Only the last line of the paragraphs are left-aligned.</p>

<p><img src="http://localhost:4001/svg/text-alignment-left-justified.svg" alt="Text Alignment Left justified" width="50%" /></p>

<p>A large majority of the text youâ€™ll set in your career will be simply left-aligned. Some will be left-justified. The others are used less frequently, and only in specific contexts that require them.</p>

<h4 id="option-1-the-perfect-page">Option #1: The Perfect Page</h4>

<p>There are many formula for creating the single-column grid. Most of them are trash, myths. There are others which are actually useful. The first is the Van de Graaf Canon. Letâ€™s dive in!</p>

<p>J.A. van de Graaf created the <a href="https://duckduckgo.com/?q=Van+de+Graaf+Canon&amp;iar=images&amp;iax=images&amp;ia=images" target="_blank">Van de Graaf Canon</a>. This is a formula to create a harmonious single-column pages.</p>

<p><strong>Weâ€™re not going to use this type of grid.</strong> I just want you to be aware of it.</p>

<p><img src="http://localhost:4001/svg/van-de-graaf-canon.svg" alt="Van De Graaf Canon" width="80%" /></p>

<p>Using these guides, no matter the dimensions of the pages, the margins will always have the same ratio. This creates margins with a ratio of: inner margin 2, top margin 3, outer margin 4, and bottom margin 6, or 2:3:4:6. We can also express this as 1/9 and 2/9 of the page.</p>

<p>There are other page layout canons. You can <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Canons_of_page_construction" target="_blank">see them here</a>.</p>

<h4 id="option-2-the-economical-approach">Option #2: The Economical Approach</h4>

<p>Here, weâ€™re going to take a more practical approach to our page layout. All we need is enough margins to accommodate the binding on the inside, our thumbs on the outside, running headers at the top and folios at the bottom.</p>

<p><img src="http://localhost:4001/svg/grimms-pages/economical-layout.svg" alt="Economical Layout" width="80%" /></p>

<p>Your pages will measure 11cm by 19cm. Youâ€™ll choose your margins. The inside margins should be larger than the outside margins.</p>

<h3 id="the-colour-of-the-page">The Colour of the Page</h3>

<p>The phrase <em>colour of the page</em> doesnâ€™t literally refer to colour itself. It refers to what the page looks like if you print one, hold it at armâ€™s length, then blur your vision. How light or dark grey is the page? The density of the content is the colour of the page. There are many factors that affect page colour, type selection, type weight, leading and letter-spacing. See some examples in this PDF.</p>

<p><a href="https://www.dropbox.com/s/b3zqqafvrb8jv8e/colour-of-the-page.pdf?dl=1" title="Download the PDF" target="_blank"><img src="http://localhost:4001/svg/button-download-pdf.svg" alt="Download a PDF" width="40%" /></a></p>

<blockquote>
  <p>Your page should have somewhere around 28 lines of text and 9-12 words per line. Consult the Info panel for the numbers.</p>
</blockquote>

<p>The goal is to create a harmonious page, free of distracting graphic elements.</p>

<h4 id="composition">Composition</h4>

<p>With no document open, open the settings for your <span class="commmand">Basic Paragraph</span> style. Go to <span class="command">Justification</span> to enter this.</p>

